regi_algo.description:
TG: REGI

Authentication and Key Agreement procedure for IMS Registration.
If set to "none", registration algorithm is not pushed into SIP Authorization header of first REGISTER at all.
In that case UE relies on 401 response from network, which contains selected algorithm.
Second (encrypted) REGISTER contains algorithm within SIP Authorization header.

auth_algo.description:
TG: REGI

Authentication Algorithm for IPSec ESP
According to 3GPP TS 33.203 clause S.5.4.2.2 it can NOT be set to "null".
Can be set either to one of the following algorithms:
    - hmac-md5-96,
    - hmac-sha-1-96,
    - hmac-sha-2-256-128,
    - hmac-sha-2-512-256,
or set to any combination of them (separated by comma), according to operator requirements, which will result in offering all listed algorithms.
When value is set neither in default section nor in operator section, "hmac-md5-96,hmac-sha-1-96" value is taken as a fallback-default.

enc_algo.description:
TG: REGI

Encryption Algorithm for IPSec ESP
Can be set either to one of the following algorithms:
    - "null"          (which means IPSec encryption "null" is proposed/accepted by UE),
    - "des-ede3-cbc",
    - "aes-cbc",
    - "aes-gcm-16",
or to any combination of them (separated by comma), according to operator requirements, which will result in offering all listed algorithms.
When value is set neither in default section nor in operator section, all options will be included in the list as a fallback-default.

reregi_on_ratchange.description:
TG: REGI

Determines whether IMS service should re-register once RAT change is observed.
Possible values are on (default, int 2 in code), off (int 0 in code) and off_rat_change (int 1 in code).
It is used in UpdateRegistration method.
Difference between off and off_rat_change is that for the latter,
the RAT change is checked and only when it is present, the registration will be held
(during execution of UpdateRegistration method).

ringing_timer.description:
TG: CALL

Applicability: MT device

Configuration used to control the automatic rejection of Incoming calls by the UE when User does not answer it in a given timer period.
The configuration specifies the Time between Incoming Call (180 Ringing sent) and Call acceptance by the User (200 Ok).
If this time period elapses and the User does not accept the call, the MT UE will send "603 No Answer" response for the Incoming INVITE request.

Value is in Seconds

ringback_timer.description:
TG: CALL

Applicability: MO Device

Configuration used to control the automatic cancellation of Outgoing calls by the UE when MT does not answer it in a given timer period.
The configuration specifies the Time between the MT device ringing (180 Ringing received) and Call acceptance by the MT User (200 Ok).
If this time period elapses and the MT does not accept the call, the MO UE will send SIP:CANCEL" request to release the Outgoing Call.

Value is in Seconds

invite_timeout.description:
TG: CALL

Applicability: MO device

When Outgoing call is initiated, this configuration, indicates the timer value which IMS stack will start after receiving 100 trying provisional response for SIP INVITE till any other SIP Response are received(1xx/2xx/3xx/4xx/5xx/6xx) from MT user/Network.
If the timer expires, then the MO device releases the outgoing call with SIP:CANCEL Request.

PN: This timer value is different from transaction timer(timer B) and retransmission timer(timer A) for SIP INVITE.

Value in seconds

The maximum duration in milliseconds that elapses between the primary (first) transmission of a frame and any redundant transmission that the sender will use.

evs_channel_aware_receive.description:
TG: CALL

If a positive (2, 3, 5, or 7) value of ch-aw-recv is declared for a payload type and the payload type is accepted, the receiver of the parameter shall send partial redundancy (channel-aware mode) at the start of the session using the value as the offset.
If ch-aw-recv=0 is declared or not present for a payload type and the payload type is accepted, the receiver of the parameter shall not send partial redundancy (channel-aware mode) at the start of the session.
If ch-aw-recv=-1 is declared for a payload type and the payload type is accepted, the receiver of the parameter shall not send partial redundancy (channel-aware mode) in the session.
If not present or a non-negative (0, 2, 3, 5, or 7) value of ch-aw-recv is declared for a payload type and the payload type is accepted, partial redundancy (channel-aware mode) can be activated or deactivated during the session based on the expected or estimated channel condition through adaptation signaling, such as CMR (see Annex A.2 of [125]) or RTCP based signalling (see clause 10.2).
If not present or a non-negative (0, 2, 3, 5, or 7) value of ch-aw-recv is declared for a payload type and the payload type is accepted, the partial redundancy offset value can also be adjusted during the session based on the expected or estimated channel condition through adaptation signaling.

evs_codec_mode_request.description:
TG: CALL

CMR (Codec Mode Request )
As per 3GPP 26.445 permissible values are -1, 0, and 1.
 If cmr is -1 and the session is in the EVS primary mode, CMR on the RTP payload header is disabled in the session. If cmr is -1 and the session is in the EVS AMR-WB IO mode, CMR in the CMR byte is restricted to the values of EVS AMR-WB IO bit-rates and NO_REQ as specified in Table A.3. 
If cmr is 0 or not present, the values of CMR specified in Table A.3 are enabled.
 If cmr is 1, CMR shall be present in each packet. CMR shall be compliant with the negotiated bit-rate and bandwidth media type attributes for EVS primary and EVS AMR-WB IO modes.

evs_bandwidth_send.description:
TG: CALL

Bandwidth in send direction
The session should start with the maximum bandwidth supported by the initial
bit-rate up to the maximum negotiated bandwidth.
If a range of bandwidth is negotiated, the codec can operate in any bandwidth
in the session but the maximum bandwidth in the range
should be used after the start of or update of the session.
If a single audio bandwidth higher than narrowband is negotiated,
the codec operates in the negotiated bandwidth but can use lower bandwidth(s)
in the session, depending on the input signal.
